#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:-1
msgid ""
"A guide to packaging Python libraries with Spack, covering PyPI downloads, "
"dependency management, and build system integration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:13
msgid "Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:15
msgid ""
"Python packages and modules have their own special build system. This "
"documentation covers everything you'll need to know in order to write a "
"Spack build recipe for a Python library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:19
msgid "Terminology"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:21
msgid ""
"In the Python ecosystem, there are a number of terms that are important to "
"understand."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:23
msgid "**PyPI**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:24
msgid ""
"The `Python Package Index <https://pypi.org/>`_, where most Python libraries "
"are hosted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:26
msgid "**sdist**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:27
msgid ""
"Source distributions, distributed as tarballs (.tar.gz) and zip files (."
"zip). Contain the source code of the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:30
msgid "**bdist**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:31
msgid ""
"Built distributions, distributed as wheels (.whl). Contain the pre-built "
"library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:34
msgid "**wheel**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:35
msgid ""
"A binary distribution format common in the Python ecosystem. This file is "
"actually just a zip file containing specific metadata and code. See the "
"`documentation <https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/specifications/binary-"
"distribution-format/>`_ for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:39
msgid "**build frontend**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:40
msgid ""
"Command-line tools used to build and install wheels. Examples include `pip "
"<https://pip.pypa.io/>`_, `build <https://pypa-build.readthedocs.io/>`_, and "
"`installer <https://installer.readthedocs.io/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:43
msgid "**build backend**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:44
msgid ""
"Libraries used to define how to build a wheel. Examples include `setuptools "
"<https://setuptools.pypa.io/>`__, `flit <https://flit.pypa.io/>`_, `poetry "
"<https://python-poetry.org/>`_, `hatchling <https://hatch.pypa.io/latest/"
">`_, `meson <https://meson-python.readthedocs.io/>`_, and `pdm <https://pdm."
"fming.dev/latest/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:48
msgid "Downloading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:50
msgid ""
"The first step in packaging a Python library is to figure out where to "
"download it from. The vast majority of Python packages are hosted on `PyPI "
"<https://pypi.org/>`_, which is :ref:`preferred over GitHub <pypi-vs-"
"github>` for downloading packages. Search for the package name on PyPI to "
"find the project page. The project page is usually located at:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:55
msgid "https://pypi.org/project/<package-name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:59
msgid ""
"On the project page, there is a \"Download files\" tab containing download "
"URLs. Whenever possible, we prefer to build Spack packages from source. If "
"PyPI only has wheels, check to see if the project is hosted on GitHub and "
"see if GitHub has source distributions. The project page usually has a "
"\"Homepage\" and/or \"Source code\" link for this. If the project is closed-"
"source, it may only have wheels available. For example, ``py-azureml-sdk`` "
"is closed-source and can be downloaded from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:66
msgid ""
"https://pypi.io/packages/py3/a/azureml_sdk/azureml_sdk-1.11.0-py3-none-any."
"whl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:70
msgid "Once you've found a URL to download the package from, run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:72
msgid "$ spack create <url>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:77
msgid "to create a new package template."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:82
msgid "PyPI vs. GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:84
msgid ""
"Many packages are hosted on PyPI, but are developed on GitHub or another "
"version control system hosting service. The source code can be downloaded "
"from either location, but PyPI is preferred for the following reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:87
msgid ""
"PyPI contains the bare minimum number of files needed to install the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:89
msgid ""
"You may notice that the tarball you download from PyPI does not have the "
"same checksum as the tarball you download from GitHub. When a developer "
"uploads a new release to PyPI, it doesn't contain every file in the "
"repository, only the files necessary to install the package. PyPI tarballs "
"are therefore smaller."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:93
msgid "PyPI is the official source for package managers like ``pip``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:95
msgid ""
"Let's be honest, ``pip`` is much more popular than Spack. If the GitHub "
"tarball contains a file not present in the PyPI tarball that causes a bug, "
"the developers may not realize this for quite some time. If the bug was in a "
"file contained in the PyPI tarball, users would notice the bug much more "
"quickly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:99
msgid "GitHub release may be a beta version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:101
msgid ""
"When a developer releases a new version of a package on GitHub, it may not "
"be intended for most users. Until that release also makes its way to PyPI, "
"it should be assumed that the release is not yet ready for general use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:104
msgid "The checksum for a GitHub release may change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:106
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, some developers have a habit of patching releases without "
"incrementing the version number. This results in a change in tarball "
"checksum. Package managers like Spack that use checksums to verify the "
"integrity of a download tarball grind to a halt when the checksum for a "
"known version changes. Most of the time, the change is intentional, and "
"contains a needed bug fix. However, sometimes the change indicates a "
"download source that has been compromised, and a tarball that contains a "
"virus. If this happens, you must contact the developers to determine which "
"is the case. PyPI is nice because it makes it physically impossible to re-"
"release the same version of a package with a different checksum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:114
msgid ""
"The only reason to use GitHub instead of PyPI is if PyPI only has wheels or "
"if the PyPI sdist is missing a file needed to build the package. If this is "
"the case, please add a comment above the ``url`` explaining this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:118
msgid "PyPI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:120
msgid ""
"Since PyPI is so commonly used to host Python libraries, the "
"``PythonPackage`` base class has a ``pypi`` attribute that can be set. Once "
"set, ``pypi`` will be used to define the ``homepage``, ``url``, and "
"``list_url``. For example, the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:124
msgid ""
"homepage = \"https://pypi.org/project/setuptools/\"\n"
"url = \"https://pypi.org/packages/source/s/setuptools/setuptools-49.2.0."
"zip\"\n"
"list_url = \"https://pypi.org/simple/setuptools/\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:131
msgid "is equivalent to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:133
msgid "pypi = \"setuptools/setuptools-49.2.0.zip\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:138
msgid ""
"If a package has a different homepage listed on PyPI, you can override it by "
"setting your own ``homepage``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:141
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:143
msgid ""
"The top of the PyPI project page contains a short description of the "
"package. The \"Project description\" tab may also contain a longer "
"description of the package. Either of these can be used to populate the "
"package docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:148
msgid "Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:150
msgid ""
"Once you've determined the basic metadata for a package, the next step is to "
"determine the build backend. ``PythonPackage`` uses `pip <https://pip.pypa."
"io/>`_ to install the package, but pip requires a backend to actually build "
"the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:153
msgid ""
"To determine the build backend, look for a ``pyproject.toml`` file. If there "
"is no ``pyproject.toml`` file and only a ``setup.py`` or ``setup.cfg`` file, "
"you can assume that the project uses :ref:`setuptools`. If there is a "
"``pyproject.toml`` file, see if it contains a ``[build-system]`` section. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:158
msgid ""
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\n"
"    \"setuptools>=42\",\n"
"    \"wheel\",\n"
"]\n"
"build-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:168
msgid ""
"This section does two things: the ``requires`` key lists build dependencies "
"of the project, and the ``build-backend`` key defines the build backend. All "
"of these build dependencies should be added as dependencies to your package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:171
msgid "depends_on(\"py-setuptools@42:\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:176
msgid ""
"Note that ``py-wheel`` is already listed as a build dependency in the "
"``PythonPackage`` base class, so you don't need to add it unless you need to "
"specify a specific version requirement or change the dependency type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:178
msgid ""
"See `PEP 517 <https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0517/>`__ and `PEP 518 "
"<https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0518/>`_ for more information on the "
"design of ``pyproject.toml``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:180
msgid ""
"Depending on which build backend a project uses, there are various places "
"that run-time dependencies can be listed. Most modern build backends support "
"listing dependencies directly in ``pyproject.toml``. Look for dependencies "
"under the following keys:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:184
msgid "``requires-python`` under ``[project]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:186
#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:223
msgid "This specifies the version of Python that is required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:188
msgid "``dependencies`` under ``[project]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:190
#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:231
#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:261
msgid ""
"These packages are required for building and installation. You can add them "
"with ``type=(\"build\", \"run\")``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:193
msgid "``[project.optional-dependencies]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:195
#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:266
msgid ""
"This section includes keys with lists of optional dependencies needed to "
"enable those features. You should add a variant that optionally adds these "
"dependencies. This variant should be ``False`` by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:199
msgid ""
"Some build backends may have additional locations where dependencies can be "
"found."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:202
msgid "distutils"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:204
msgid ""
"Before the introduction of setuptools and other build backends, Python "
"packages had to rely on the built-in distutils library. Distutils is missing "
"many of the features that setuptools and other build backends offer, and "
"users are encouraged to use setuptools instead. In fact, distutils was "
"deprecated in Python 3.10 and will be removed in Python 3.12. Because of "
"this, pip actually replaces all imports of distutils with setuptools. If a "
"package uses distutils, you should instead add a build dependency on "
"setuptools. Check for a ``requirements.txt`` file that may list dependencies "
"of the project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:214
msgid "setuptools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:216
msgid ""
"If the ``pyproject.toml`` lists ``setuptools.build_meta`` as a ``build-"
"backend``, or if the package has a ``setup.py`` that imports ``setuptools``, "
"or if the package has a ``setup.cfg`` file, then it uses setuptools to "
"build. Setuptools is a replacement for the distutils library, and has almost "
"the exact same API. In addition to ``pyproject.toml``, dependencies can be "
"listed in the ``setup.py`` or ``setup.cfg`` file. Look for the following "
"arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:221
msgid "``python_requires``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:225
msgid "``setup_requires``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:227
msgid ""
"These packages are usually only needed at build-time, so you can add them "
"with ``type=\"build\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:229
msgid "``install_requires``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:234
msgid "``extras_require``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:236
msgid ""
"These packages are optional dependencies that enable additional "
"functionality. You should add a variant that optionally adds these "
"dependencies. This variant should be ``False`` by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:240
msgid "``tests_require``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:242
msgid ""
"These are packages that are required to run the unit tests for the package. "
"These dependencies can be specified using the ``type=\"test\"`` dependency "
"type. However, the PyPI tarballs rarely contain unit tests, so there is "
"usually no reason to add these."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:246
msgid ""
"See https://setuptools.pypa.io/en/latest/userguide/dependency_management."
"html for more information on how setuptools handles dependency management. "
"See `PEP 440 <https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0440/#version-"
"specifiers>`_ for documentation on version specifiers in setuptools."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:250
msgid "flit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:252
msgid ""
"There are actually two possible build backends for flit, ``flit`` and "
"``flit_core``. If you see these in the ``pyproject.toml``, add a build "
"dependency to your package. With flit, all dependencies are listed directly "
"in the ``pyproject.toml`` file. Older versions of flit used to store this "
"info in a ``flit.ini`` file, so check for this too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:257
msgid ""
"In addition to the default ``pyproject.toml`` keys listed above, older "
"versions of flit may use the following keys:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:259
msgid "``requires`` under ``[tool.flit.metadata]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:264
msgid "``[tool.flit.metadata.requires-extra]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:270
msgid ""
"See https://flit.pypa.io/en/latest/pyproject_toml.html for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:273
msgid "poetry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:275
msgid ""
"Like flit, poetry also has two possible build backends, ``poetry`` and "
"``poetry_core``. If you see these in the ``pyproject.toml``, add a build "
"dependency to your package. With poetry, all dependencies are listed "
"directly in the ``pyproject.toml`` file. Dependencies are listed in a "
"``[tool.poetry.dependencies]`` section, and use a `custom syntax <https://"
"python-poetry.org/docs/dependency-specification/#version-constraints>`_ for "
"specifying the version requirements. Note that ``~=`` works differently in "
"poetry than in setuptools and flit for versions that start with a zero."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:282
msgid "hatchling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:284
msgid ""
"If the ``pyproject.toml`` lists ``hatchling.build`` as the ``build-"
"backend``, it uses the hatchling build system. Hatchling uses the default "
"``pyproject.toml`` keys to list dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:287
msgid ""
"See https://hatch.pypa.io/latest/config/dependency/ for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:290
msgid "meson"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:292
msgid ""
"If the ``pyproject.toml`` lists ``mesonpy`` as the ``build-backend``, it "
"uses the meson build system. Meson uses the default ``pyproject.toml`` keys "
"to list dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:295
msgid ""
"See https://meson-python.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/introduction."
"html for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:298
msgid "pdm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:300
msgid ""
"If the ``pyproject.toml`` lists ``pdm.pep517.api`` as the ``build-backend``, "
"it uses the PDM build system. PDM uses the default ``pyproject.toml`` keys "
"to list dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:303
msgid "See https://pdm.fming.dev/latest/ for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:306
msgid "wheels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:308
msgid ""
"Some Python packages are closed-source and are distributed as Python wheels. "
"For example, ``py-azureml-sdk`` downloads a ``.whl`` file. This file is "
"simply a zip file, and can be extracted using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:312
msgid "$ unzip *.whl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:317
msgid ""
"The zip file will not contain a ``setup.py``, but it will contain a "
"``METADATA`` file which contains all the information you need to write a "
"``package.py`` build recipe. Check for lines like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:320
msgid ""
"Requires-Python: >=3.5,<4\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-core (~=1.11.0)\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-dataset-runtime[fuse] (~=1.11.0)\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-train (~=1.11.0)\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-train-automl-client (~=1.11.0)\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-pipeline (~=1.11.0)\n"
"Provides-Extra: accel-models\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-accel-models (~=1.11.0); extra == 'accel-models'\n"
"Provides-Extra: automl\n"
"Requires-Dist: azureml-train-automl (~=1.11.0); extra == 'automl'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:334
msgid ""
"``Requires-Python`` is equivalent to ``python_requires`` and ``Requires-"
"Dist`` is equivalent to ``install_requires``. ``Provides-Extra`` is used to "
"name optional features (variants) and a ``Requires-Dist`` with ``extra == "
"'foo'`` will list any dependencies needed for that feature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:338
msgid "Passing arguments to setup.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:340
msgid ""
"The default install phase should be sufficient to install most packages. "
"However, the installation instructions for a package may suggest passing "
"certain flags to the ``setup.py`` call. The ``PythonPackage`` class has two "
"techniques for doing this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:345
msgid "Config settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:347
msgid ""
"These settings are passed to `PEP 517 <https://peps.python.org/pep-0517/>`__ "
"build backends. For example, ``py-scipy`` package allows you to specify the "
"name of the BLAS/LAPACK library you want pkg-config to search for:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:350
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"py-pip@22.1:\", type=\"build\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def config_settings(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    return {\n"
"        \"blas\": spec[\"blas\"].libs.names[0],\n"
"        \"lapack\": spec[\"lapack\"].libs.names[0],\n"
"    }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:364
msgid ""
"This flag only works for packages that define a ``build-backend`` in "
"``pyproject.toml``. Also, it is only supported by pip 22.1+, which requires "
"Python 3.7+. For packages that still support Python 3.6 and older, "
"``install_options`` should be used instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:370
msgid "Global options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:372
msgid ""
"These flags are added directly after ``setup.py`` when pip runs ``python "
"setup.py install``. For example, the ``py-pyyaml`` package has an optional "
"dependency on ``libyaml`` that can be enabled like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:375
msgid ""
"def global_options(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    options = []\n"
"    if spec.satisfies(\"+libyaml\"):\n"
"        options.append(\"--with-libyaml\")\n"
"    else:\n"
"        options.append(\"--without-libyaml\")\n"
"    return options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:388
#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:415
msgid ""
"Direct invocation of ``setup.py`` is `deprecated <https://blog.ganssle.io/"
"articles/2021/10/setup-py-deprecated.html>`_. This flag forces pip to use a "
"deprecated installation procedure. It should only be used in packages that "
"don't define a ``build-backend`` in ``pyproject.toml`` or packages that "
"still support Python 3.6 and older."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:394
msgid "Install options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:396
msgid ""
"These flags are added directly after ``install`` when pip runs ``python "
"setup.py install``. For example, the ``py-pyyaml`` package allows you to "
"specify the directories to search for ``libyaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:399
msgid ""
"def install_options(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    options = []\n"
"    if spec.satisfies(\"+libyaml\"):\n"
"        options.extend(\n"
"            [\n"
"                spec[\"libyaml\"].libs.search_flags,\n"
"                spec[\"libyaml\"].headers.include_flags,\n"
"            ]\n"
"        )\n"
"    return options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:421
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:423
msgid ""
"``PythonPackage`` provides a couple of options for testing packages both "
"during and after the installation process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:426
msgid "Import tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:428
msgid ""
"Just because a package successfully built does not mean that it built "
"correctly. The most reliable test of whether or not the package was "
"correctly installed is to attempt to import all of the modules that get "
"installed. To get a list of modules, run the following command in the source "
"directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:432
msgid ""
">>> import setuptools\n"
">>> setuptools.find_packages()\n"
"['numpy', 'numpy._build_utils', 'numpy.compat', 'numpy.core', 'numpy."
"distutils', 'numpy.doc', 'numpy.f2py', 'numpy.fft', 'numpy.lib', 'numpy."
"linalg', 'numpy.ma', 'numpy.matrixlib', 'numpy.polynomial', 'numpy.random', "
"'numpy.testing', 'numpy.core.code_generators', 'numpy.distutils.command', "
"'numpy.distutils.fcompiler']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:439
msgid ""
"Large, complex packages like ``numpy`` will return a long list of packages, "
"while other packages like ``six`` will return an empty list. ``py-six`` "
"installs a single ``six.py`` file. In Python packaging lingo, a \"package\" "
"is a directory containing files like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:443
msgid ""
"foo/__init__.py\n"
"foo/bar.py\n"
"foo/baz.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:450
msgid "whereas a \"module\" is a single Python file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:452
msgid ""
"The ``PythonPackage`` base class automatically detects these package and "
"module names for you. If, for whatever reason, the module names detected are "
"wrong, you can provide the names yourself by overriding ``import_modules`` "
"like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:455
msgid "import_modules = [\"six\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:460
msgid ""
"Sometimes the list of module names to import depends on how the package was "
"built. For example, the ``py-pyyaml`` package has a ``+libyaml`` variant "
"that enables the build of a faster optimized version of the library. If the "
"user chooses ``~libyaml``, only the ``yaml`` library will be importable. If "
"the user chooses ``+libyaml``, both the ``yaml`` and ``yaml.cyaml`` "
"libraries will be available. This can be expressed like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:466
msgid ""
"@property\n"
"def import_modules(self):\n"
"    modules = [\"yaml\"]\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"+libyaml\"):\n"
"        modules.append(\"yaml.cyaml\")\n"
"    return modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:476
msgid ""
"These tests often catch missing dependencies and non-RPATHed libraries. Make "
"sure not to add modules/packages containing the word \"test\", as these "
"likely won't end up in the installation directory, or may require test "
"dependencies like pytest to be installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:479
msgid ""
"Instead of defining the ``import_modules`` explicitly, only the subset of "
"module names to be skipped can be defined by using ``skip_modules``. If a "
"defined module has submodules, they are skipped as well, e.g., in case the "
"``plotting`` modules should be excluded from the automatically detected "
"``import_modules`` ``[\"nilearn\", \"nilearn.surface\", \"nilearn."
"plotting\", \"nilearn.plotting.data\"]`` set:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:482
msgid "skip_modules = [\"nilearn.plotting\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:486
msgid ""
"This will set ``import_modules`` to ``[\"nilearn\", \"nilearn.surface\"]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:488
msgid ""
"Import tests can be run during the installation using ``spack install --"
"test=root`` or at any time after the installation using ``spack test run``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:491
msgid "Unit tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:493
msgid ""
"The package may have its own unit or regression tests. Spack can run these "
"tests during the installation by adding test methods after installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:496
msgid ""
"For example, ``py-numpy`` adds the following as a check to run after the "
"``install`` phase:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:498
msgid ""
"@run_after(\"install\")\n"
"@on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"def install_test(self):\n"
"    with working_dir(\"spack-test\", create=True):\n"
"        python(\"-c\", \"import numpy; numpy.test('full', verbose=2)\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:507
msgid ""
"when testing is enabled during the installation (i.e., ``spack install --"
"test=root``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:511
msgid ""
"Additional information is available on :ref:`install phase tests "
"<install_phase-tests>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:514
msgid "Setup file in a sub-directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:516
msgid ""
"Many C/C++ libraries provide optional Python bindings in a subdirectory. To "
"tell pip which directory to build from, you can override the "
"``build_directory`` attribute. For example, if a package provides Python "
"bindings in a ``python`` directory, you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:520
msgid "build_directory = \"python\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:526
msgid "PythonPackage vs. packages that use Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:528
msgid ""
"There are many packages that make use of Python, but packages that depend on "
"Python are not necessarily ``PythonPackage``'s."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:531
msgid "Choosing a build system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:533
msgid ""
"First of all, you need to select a build system. ``spack create`` usually "
"does this for you, but if for whatever reason you need to do this manually, "
"choose ``PythonPackage`` if and only if the package contains one of the "
"following files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:536
msgid "``pyproject.toml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:537
msgid "``setup.py``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:538
msgid "``setup.cfg``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:541
msgid "Choosing a package name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:543
msgid ""
"Selecting the appropriate package name is a little more complicated than "
"choosing the build system. By default, ``spack create`` will prepend ``py-`` "
"to the beginning of the package name if it detects that the package uses the "
"``PythonPackage`` build system. However, there are occasionally packages "
"that use ``PythonPackage`` that shouldn't start with ``py-``. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:548
msgid "awscli"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:549
msgid "aws-parallelcluster"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:550
msgid "busco"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:551
msgid "easybuild"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:552
msgid "httpie"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:553
msgid "mercurial"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:554
msgid "scons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:555
msgid "snakemake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:557
msgid ""
"The thing these packages have in common is that they are command-line tools "
"that just so happen to be written in Python. Someone who wants to install "
"``mercurial`` with Spack isn't going to realize that it is written in "
"Python, and they certainly aren't going to assume the package is called ``py-"
"mercurial``. For this reason, we manually renamed the package to "
"``mercurial``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:561
msgid ""
"Likewise, there are occasionally packages that don't use the "
"``PythonPackage`` build system but should still be prepended with ``py-``. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:564
msgid "py-genders"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:565
msgid "py-py2cairo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:566
msgid "py-pygobject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:567
msgid "py-pygtk"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:568
msgid "py-pyqt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:569
msgid "py-pyserial"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:570
msgid "py-sip"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:571
msgid "py-xpyb"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:573
msgid ""
"These packages are primarily used as Python libraries, not as command-line "
"tools. You may see C/C++ packages that have optional Python language "
"bindings, such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:576
msgid "antlr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:577
msgid "cantera"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:578
msgid "conduit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:579
msgid "pagmo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:580
msgid "vtk"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:582
msgid ""
"Don't prepend these kinds of packages with ``py-``. When in doubt, think "
"about how this package will be used. Is it primarily a Python library that "
"will be imported in other Python scripts? Or is it a command-line tool, or C/"
"C++/Fortran program with optional Python modules? The former should be "
"prepended with ``py-``, while the latter should not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:589
msgid "``extends`` vs. ``depends_on``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:591
msgid ""
"As mentioned in the :ref:`Packaging Guide <packaging_extensions>`, "
"``extends`` and ``depends_on`` are very similar, but ``extends`` ensures "
"that the extension and extendee share the same prefix in views. This allows "
"the user to import a Python module without having to add that module to "
"``PYTHONPATH``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:594
msgid ""
"Additionally, ``extends(\"python\")`` adds a dependency on the package "
"``python-venv``. This improves isolation from the system, whether it's "
"during the build or at runtime: user and system site packages cannot "
"accidentally be used by any package that ``extends(\"python\")``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:597
msgid ""
"As a rule of thumb: if a package does not install any Python modules of its "
"own, and merely puts a Python script in the ``bin`` directory, then there is "
"no need for ``extends``. If the package installs modules in the ``site-"
"packages`` directory, it requires ``extends``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:601
msgid "Executing ``python`` during the build"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:603
msgid ""
"Whenever you need to execute a Python command or pass the path of the Python "
"interpreter to the build system, it is best to use the global variable "
"``python`` directly. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:606
msgid ""
"@run_before(\"install\")\n"
"def recythonize(self):\n"
"    python(\"setup.py\", \"clean\")  # use the `python` global"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:612
msgid ""
"As mentioned in the previous section, ``extends(\"python\")`` adds an "
"automatic dependency on ``python-venv``, which is a virtual environment that "
"guarantees build isolation. The ``python`` global always refers to the "
"correct Python interpreter, whether the package uses ``extends(\"python\")`` "
"or ``depends_on(\"python\")``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:616
msgid "Alternatives to Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:618
msgid ""
"PyPI has hundreds of thousands of packages that are not yet in Spack, and "
"``pip`` may be a perfectly valid alternative to using Spack. The main "
"advantage of Spack over ``pip`` is its ability to compile non-Python "
"dependencies. It can also build cythonized versions of a package or link to "
"an optimized BLAS/LAPACK library like MKL, resulting in calculations that "
"run orders of magnitude faster. Spack does not offer a significant advantage "
"over other Python-management systems for installing and using tools like "
"flake8 and sphinx. But if you need packages with non-Python dependencies "
"like numpy and scipy, Spack will be very valuable to you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/pythonpackage.rst:624
msgid ""
"Anaconda is another great alternative to Spack, and comes with its own "
"``conda`` package manager. Like Spack, Anaconda is capable of compiling non-"
"Python dependencies. Anaconda contains many Python packages that are not yet "
"in Spack, and Spack contains many Python packages that are not yet in "
"Anaconda. The main advantage of Spack over Anaconda is its ability to choose "
"a specific compiler and BLAS/LAPACK or MPI library. Spack also has better "
"platform support for supercomputers, and can build optimized binaries for "
"your specific microarchitecture."
msgstr ""

